      "h": "Why 'Texican' Matters: Identity and History",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> This lesson begins by exploring the term 'Texican,' a historically rich and contested identity linked to early Texas settlers of Spanish and Mexican heritage. We will clarify its meaning and origins to build a solid foundation for understanding their role in Texas history.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from jinxschwartz.com; everything-everywhere.com; youtube.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Introduction to the term 'Texican' and its historical context</li><li>Understanding the complexities and contested meanings</li><li>Setting goals for this lesson section</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Consider how 'Texican' differs from 'Texan'—the former often refers to early Hispanic settlers, while the latter is a broader term for all Texas residents.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Reflect on your current understanding of 'Texican.' How might it differ from 'Texan' or other regional identities?</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Confusing 'Texican' with 'Texan' without recognizing the cultural and historical distinctions.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> jinxschwartz.com; everything-everywhere.com; youtube.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s5\">[5]</sup></p>"
