    "eyebrow": "Settlement Patterns",
    "num": "13",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">13</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Settlement Patterns</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Migration Routes of Early Texicans</h2><ul><li>Texicans migrated primarily from northern Mexico into Spanish Texas</li><li>Settlements clustered along rivers and fertile land for agriculture</li><li>Migration influenced by Spanish land grant policies and frontier defense needs</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texicans moved into Spanish Texas following established routes, often settling near water sources to support farming and ranching. Spanish colonial policies encouraged settlement through land grants, shaping where and how Texicans established communities. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s11\">[11]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> The San Antonio River area became a key settlement zone due to its water supply and fertile soil, attracting many Texican families.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Identify why proximity to rivers was critical for Texican settlements.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming Texican migration was random rather than influenced by colonial policies and geography.</p></div></div>",
