      "h": "Analyzing Texican Migration Influences",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Texicans moved into Spanish Texas following established routes, often settling near water sources to support farming and ranching. Spanish colonial policies encouraged settlement through land grants, shaping where and how Texicans established communities.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from jinxschwartz.com; libguides.tamusa.edu; texasstudies.org. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Texicans migrated primarily from northern Mexico into Spanish Texas</li><li>Settlements clustered along rivers and fertile land for agriculture</li><li>Migration influenced by Spanish land grant policies and frontier defense needs</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>The San Antonio River area became a key settlement zone due to its water supply and fertile soil, attracting many Texican families.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Identify why proximity to rivers was critical for Texican settlements.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Assuming Texican migration was random rather than influenced by colonial policies and geography.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> jinxschwartz.com; libguides.tamusa.edu; texasstudies.org <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s11\">[11]</sup></p>"
