    "eyebrow": "Family Life",
    "num": "14",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">14</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Family Life</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Texican Family Structures and Roles</h2><ul><li>Extended families were common, often living in multi-generational households</li><li>Family roles were influenced by Spanish and Mexican traditions</li><li>Women managed household duties and contributed to agricultural work</li><li>Children learned skills early to support family economy</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texican families typically included multiple generations living together, reflecting Spanish colonial social norms. Women played key roles in both domestic management and farming, while children were integrated into family labor from a young age. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A Texican family might include grandparents, parents, children, and sometimes cousins, all contributing to ranching and farming tasks.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Describe how Texican family roles supported frontier survival.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Overlooking women's economic contributions beyond domestic chores.</p></div></div>",
