    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">16</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Settlement Patterns</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Land Use and Economic Activities of Texicans</h2><ul><li>Ranching and cattle raising were primary economic activities</li><li>Small-scale farming supplemented ranching for family sustenance</li><li>Land was often communally managed within settlements</li><li>Trade with nearby Mexican and indigenous communities supported economy</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texicans’ economy centered on cattle ranching, which suited the open landscapes of Texas. Farming provided food for families, while trade networks helped acquire goods not locally produced. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s11\">[11]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A Texican rancher raised cattle for hides and meat, trading surplus with indigenous groups for tools and foodstuffs.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Identify how ranching shaped Texican settlement layouts.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming Texican economy was solely agricultural without trade.</p></div></div>",
