    "num": "17",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">17</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Daily Life</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Housing and Material Culture of Texicans</h2><ul><li>Homes were typically adobe or wood structures adapted to local climate</li><li>Furniture and tools reflected a blend of Spanish and indigenous influences</li><li>Households included religious artifacts reflecting Catholic faith</li><li>Material culture was practical, emphasizing durability and resourcefulness</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texican homes combined Spanish architectural styles with adaptations to Texas’s environment. Material culture was shaped by available resources and cultural traditions, reflecting a hybrid identity. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s11\">[11]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Adobe walls provided insulation against heat and cold, while simple wooden furniture was handcrafted by settlers.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Describe how Texican housing adapted to frontier conditions.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming Texican homes were identical to European-style houses without adaptation.</p></div></div>",
