    "num": "18",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">18</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Social Organization</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Community Structures and Governance Among Texicans</h2><ul><li>Settlements organized around presidios and missions for protection and social order</li><li>Local councils (ayuntamientos) managed community affairs</li><li>Social hierarchy included landowners, ranchers, and laborers</li><li>Religious institutions played central roles in community cohesion</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texican communities were structured with formal and informal governance, combining Spanish colonial institutions with frontier adaptations. Religion and social status influenced community dynamics. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s11\">[11]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A local ayuntamiento would resolve disputes and organize defense against raids.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Explain how governance structures supported Texican community stability.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Ignoring the role of missions and presidios beyond religious functions.</p></div></div>",
