    "id": "slide20",
    "eyebrow": "Migration Motivations",
    "num": "20",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">20</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Migration Motivations</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Why Texicans Moved to Texas: Economic and Political Factors</h2><ul><li>Economic opportunities in land and ranching attracted settlers</li><li>Spanish and Mexican governments encouraged settlement for territorial control</li><li>Some migrated to escape political instability or seek new beginnings</li><li>Family networks facilitated chain migration</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texican migration was driven by a mix of economic prospects and government incentives, alongside personal and political motivations. Family ties often influenced migration decisions. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A family from northern Mexico might relocate to Texas to claim land grants and establish a ranch.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Identify key factors motivating Texican migration to Texas.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Viewing migration solely as economic without political context.</p></div></div>",
