      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Texican migration was driven by a mix of economic prospects and government incentives, alongside personal and political motivations. Family ties often influenced migration decisions.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from jinxschwartz.com; libguides.tamusa.edu. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Economic opportunities in land and ranching attracted settlers</li><li>Spanish and Mexican governments encouraged settlement for territorial control</li><li>Some migrated to escape political instability or seek new beginnings</li><li>Family networks facilitated chain migration</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>A family from northern Mexico might relocate to Texas to claim land grants and establish a ranch.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Identify key factors motivating Texican migration to Texas.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Viewing migration solely as economic without political context.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> jinxschwartz.com; libguides.tamusa.edu <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup></p>"
