    "id": "slide26",
    "eyebrow": "Cultural Identity",
    "num": "26",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">26</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Cultural Identity</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Mexican Influences and Texican Adaptations</h2><ul><li>Mexican independence introduced new political and cultural dynamics</li><li>Texicans adopted Mexican legal codes and citizenship</li><li>Cultural blending with indigenous and Spanish traditions continued</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">After Mexico gained independence, Texicans became Mexican citizens and adapted to new laws and political structures. However, they retained many Spanish cultural elements while also incorporating indigenous influences, creating a unique cultural blend. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s13\">[13]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Texican communities celebrated Mexican national holidays alongside traditional Catholic festivals.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Discuss how Mexican independence might have changed Texican political identity without erasing cultural traditions.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Viewing Texican culture as static rather than evolving through Mexican political changes.</p></div></div>",
