      "secnum": "Deep Dive 26",
      "h": "Mexican Political and Cultural Influence on Texicans",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> After Mexico gained independence, Texicans became Mexican citizens and adapted to new laws and political structures. However, they retained many Spanish cultural elements while also incorporating indigenous influences, creating a unique cultural blend.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from jinxschwartz.com; everything-everywhere.com; kwlibguides.lonestar.edu. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Mexican independence introduced new political and cultural dynamics</li><li>Texicans adopted Mexican legal codes and citizenship</li><li>Cultural blending with indigenous and Spanish traditions continued</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Texican communities celebrated Mexican national holidays alongside traditional Catholic festivals.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Discuss how Mexican independence might have changed Texican political identity without erasing cultural traditions.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Viewing Texican culture as static rather than evolving through Mexican political changes.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> jinxschwartz.com; everything-everywhere.com; kwlibguides.lonestar.edu <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s13\">[13]</sup></p>"
