      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Indigenous cultures significantly influenced Texican identity through shared customs, intermarriage, and practical knowledge. This interaction enriched Texican culture beyond Spanish and Mexican roots.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from jinxschwartz.com; everything-everywhere.com; legacy.education.texashistory.unt.edu. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Indigenous peoples contributed language, food, and customs</li><li>Texicans engaged in trade and intermarriage with native groups</li><li>Indigenous knowledge influenced Texican agriculture and survival</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Texican diets incorporated indigenous crops like corn and beans, and some families had indigenous ancestry.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Identify examples of indigenous cultural contributions to Texican daily life.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Ignoring indigenous influence or treating Texican culture as solely European-derived.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> jinxschwartz.com; everything-everywhere.com; legacy.education.texashistory.unt.edu <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s12\">[12]</sup></p>"
