    "eyebrow": "Identity Formation",
    "num": "28",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">28</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Identity Formation</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">How Mixed Influences Created a Unique Texican Identity</h2><ul><li>Texican identity combined Spanish, Mexican, and indigenous elements</li><li>This hybrid identity distinguished Texicans from Anglo settlers</li><li>Cultural practices reflected adaptation to frontier life and politics</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">The Texican identity emerged as a distinct cultural blend shaped by multiple heritages and frontier experiences. This identity was neither fully Mexican nor Anglo-American but a unique synthesis. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s13\">[13]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Texican music and dance incorporated Spanish melodies with indigenous rhythms and Mexican themes.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Explain how cultural blending helped Texicans maintain community cohesion amid political change.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming Texican identity was monolithic or static over time.</p></div></div>",
