    "num": "29",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">29</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Historical Role</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Texicans’ Political Loyalties Before the Texas Revolution</h2><ul><li>Texicans initially loyal to Mexico but wary of central government policies</li><li>Many supported federalism and local autonomy</li><li>Tensions grew over immigration and land rights with Anglo settlers</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Before the Texas Revolution, Texicans generally supported Mexican federalism but became increasingly concerned about centralist policies and Anglo immigration, which threatened their land and political influence. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Texican leaders petitioned Mexican authorities for protection of their land grants and local governance.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Analyze how Texican political loyalties were influenced by Mexican government actions and Anglo immigration.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming all Texicans uniformly supported or opposed the Mexican government.</p></div></div>",
