      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Before the Texas Revolution, Texicans generally supported Mexican federalism but became increasingly concerned about centralist policies and Anglo immigration, which threatened their land and political influence.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from jinxschwartz.com; everything-everywhere.com; britannica.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Texicans initially loyal to Mexico but wary of central government policies</li><li>Many supported federalism and local autonomy</li><li>Tensions grew over immigration and land rights with Anglo settlers</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Texican leaders petitioned Mexican authorities for protection of their land grants and local governance.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Analyze how Texican political loyalties were influenced by Mexican government actions and Anglo immigration.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Assuming all Texicans uniformly supported or opposed the Mexican government.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> jinxschwartz.com; everything-everywhere.com; britannica.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup></p>"
