    "eyebrow": "Primary Sources",
    "num": "39",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">39</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Primary Sources</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Legal Documents: Property and Land Ownership</h2><ul><li>Land grants and deeds show settlement patterns and economic priorities.</li><li>Legal disputes reveal conflicts over land and resources.</li><li>Documents reflect Spanish and Mexican legal traditions.</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Legal records provide concrete evidence of Texican settlement, land use, and social organization under Spanish and Mexican law. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s15\">[15]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s16\">[16]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A land grant document details acreage awarded to a Texican family, specifying boundaries and obligations.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Examine a land deed excerpt: What does it tell you about Texican settlement and legal rights?</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Ignoring the influence of Spanish legal customs on Texican property laws.</p></div></div>",
