    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">40</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Primary Sources</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Political Views in Texican Correspondence</h2><ul><li>Letters express varied loyalties: Mexican, Texican, and emerging Texan identities.</li><li>Political tensions are evident in discussions of governance and revolution.</li><li>Some letters reveal fears and hopes about Texas independence.</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texican letters provide direct insight into political sentiments during the Texas Revolution and early statehood periods. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s17\">[17]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A letter debates loyalty to Mexico versus support for Texan independence, reflecting internal community divisions.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Identify political attitudes in a letter excerpt and discuss their implications for Texican identity.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming uniform political loyalty among Texicans; primary sources show diversity.</p></div></div>",
