    "num": "56",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">56</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Contested Perspectives</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Political Loyalties: Texicans in Historical Debate</h2><ul><li>Some portray Texicans as divided between loyalty to Mexico and Texas independence</li><li>Others argue Texicans predominantly supported the Texan cause</li><li>Disagreements arise from differing interpretations of military and political records</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texican political loyalties during the Texas Revolution remain debated, with historians interpreting evidence differently regarding their predominant allegiance. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s9\">[9]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Military records show Texicans fighting on both sides, complicating a unified narrative.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Assess how conflicting evidence affects understanding of Texican political loyalties.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Ignoring conflicting evidence leads to oversimplified conclusions about Texican loyalties.</p></div></div>",
