      "h": "Analyzing Conflicting Evidence on Texican Loyalties",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Texican political loyalties during the Texas Revolution remain debated, with historians interpreting evidence differently regarding their predominant allegiance.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from jinxschwartz.com; everything-everywhere.com; britannica.com; thestoryoftexas.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Some portray Texicans as divided between loyalty to Mexico and Texas independence</li><li>Others argue Texicans predominantly supported the Texan cause</li><li>Disagreements arise from differing interpretations of military and political records</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Military records show Texicans fighting on both sides, complicating a unified narrative.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Assess how conflicting evidence affects understanding of Texican political loyalties.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Ignoring conflicting evidence leads to oversimplified conclusions about Texican loyalties.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> jinxschwartz.com; everything-everywhere.com; britannica.com; thestoryoftexas.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s9\">[9]</sup></p>"
