    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">58</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Contested Perspectives</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Evaluating Primary Sources on Texican Identity</h2><ul><li>Primary sources include letters, diaries, legal documents, and official records</li><li>These sources reveal diverse Texican experiences and viewpoints</li><li>Critical analysis is needed to interpret biases and context</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Primary sources provide direct evidence of Texican life and identity but require careful evaluation to understand their perspectives and limitations. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s11\">[11]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s12\">[12]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s13\">[13]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A Texican letter expressing loyalty to Mexico contrasts with a diary supporting Texas independence.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Analyze a primary source excerpt to identify the author's perspective and potential bias.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Taking primary sources at face value without considering context can lead to misinterpretation.</p></div></div>",
